<SECTION1 LBL="" HELPID = ""><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="31405">Obtaining a Software Distribution<INDEXTARGET ID="ch021"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch021|distribution software --></TITLE><PARAGRAPH>Share trees, client trees, and swap trees should be created from an official release of Silicon Graphics software. Silicon Graphics software is originally distributed on compact disc with read-only memory (CD-ROM). On some networks, a copy of this software is available from a central distribution source on the network. You can use either source to install diskless software, as long as you use an official software release.<INDEXTARGET ID="ch022"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch022|IRIX:distribution media --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>At minimum, the IRIX 6.5 source must include the Silicon Graphics Execution Only Environment product (<INDEXTARGET ID="ch023"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch023|installation software requirements --><FILENAME>eoe</FILENAME>) and its supporting software, and the NFS product option, <FILENAME>nfs</FILENAME>. A group of subsystems from each of these products is required to install diskless software (see <XREF IDREF="31625" TYPE="TABLE">Table&nbsp;2-2</XREF> for details). </PARAGRAPH>
</SECTION1>
<SECTION1 LBL="" HELPID = ""><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="37539">Checking a Server<INDEXTARGET ID="ch024"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch024|server:checking suitability of --></TITLE><PARAGRAPH>Use the questions that follow to evaluate the suitability of a server on which you plan to install the diskless tree. If you determine that any procedure described in this section is necessary, complete the procedure before you begin diskless installation. </PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>1. Is the server reliable?</BOLD><INDEXTARGET ID="ch025"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch025|server:reliability requirements --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>The ideal choice for a diskless server is a network host that is able to provide uninterrupted service to its clients for extended periods of time. Hosts that are subject to frequent shutdowns, such as laboratory systems, those used for software builds, or hosts subject to interruptions in service, are not likely to prove satisfactory as diskless servers. </PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>2. Does the server have ample disk space?</BOLD>&space;<INDEXTARGET ID="ch026"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch026|server:disk space on --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>On average, approximately 1 gigabyte (GB) of disk space is required for a diskless tree with these characteristics: <INDEXTARGET ID="ch027"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch027|diskless tree:space requirements for --><INDEXTARGET ID="ch028"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch028|disk space:for diskless tree --></PARAGRAPH>
<BULLETLIST><BULLET><PARAGRAPH>One share tree of IRIX 6.5 with a minimum software configuration (see <XREF IDREF="31625" TYPE="TABLE">Table&nbsp;2-2</XREF>)</PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
<BULLET><PARAGRAPH>Five client trees with a minimal software configuration </PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
<BULLET><PARAGRAPH>Five swap trees, each containing 64 megabytes (MB) of swap space </PARAGRAPH>
</BULLET>
</BULLETLIST>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>3. Is the server running the necessary software?</BOLD>&space;<INDEXTARGET ID="ch029"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch029|IRIX:version compatibility --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>The IRIX version implemented on a server must be the same as or more recent than the IRIX version of any share tree that it supports. In addition, a server running 32-bit IRIX cannot support share trees of 64-bit IRIX. See the release notes shipped with your software for more specific compatibility information. <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0210"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0210|compatibility (of IRIX versions) --><INDEXTARGET ID="ch0211"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0211|server:IRIX version on --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>To determine the version of IRIX running on a server, use the <COMMAND>uname</COMMAND> command with the release option (<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0212"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0212|<ITALICS>uname</ITALICS> command --><CMDLINEOPT>-r</CMDLINEOPT>), as shown in the following example. Do not install a share tree with a higher revision level than appears in the output from this command: </PARAGRAPH>
<EXAMPLE>
% <USERINPUT>uname -r&lbreak;</USERINPUT>6.5 
</EXAMPLE>
<PARAGRAPH>You should also verify that the host acting as the diskless server is running nfs.sw.diskless_server, the software subsystem that supports the diskless server function. To verify, enter the <COMMAND>versions</COMMAND> command and look for the diskless server subsystem in the command bitoutput, as shown in this example:</PARAGRAPH>
<EXAMPLE>
% <USERINPUT>versions nfs&lbreak;</USERINPUT>I  nfs.sw.dskless_server  08/18/97  Diskless Server Support
</EXAMPLE>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>4. Is the TFTP environment set up correctly?</BOLD>&space;</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Client boot files are transferred from the server by means of the trivial file transfer protocol (TFTP). The server must contain a user account that owns TFTP (see the <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0213"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0213|<ITALICS>tftp</ITALICS> protocol --><REFPAGE>tftp</REFPAGE> reference page). By default, the owner of TFTP is <ITALICS>guest</ITALICS>. If you want a user other than <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0214"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0214|guest account --><ITALICS>guest</ITALICS> to own TFTP (for security reasons, for example), you must modify the file<FILENAME>&space;/etc/inetd.conf<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0215"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0215|<ITALICS>/etc/inetd.conf</ITALICS> file --></FILENAME> to specify a different owner (see the <REFPAGE>inetd</REFPAGE> reference page). If you plan to install software by downloading it from a remote host, be sure that TFTP security is correctly configured on the remote system (see <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0216"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0216|<ITALICS>inetd</ITALICS> server --><REFPAGE>tftpd</REFPAGE>). </PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>5. Is an NIS domain name assigned to the server?</BOLD>&space;<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0217"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0217|network information service.  <ITALICS>See</ITALICS> NIS. --><INDEXTARGET ID="ch0218"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0218|NIS:setting domain names for --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>To support diskless clients, a server must have an NIS domain name, whether or not it is running the network information service (NIS). To determine whether a server has an NIS domain name, use the <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0219"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0219|domain name: setting --><REFPAGE>domainname</REFPAGE> command: <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0220"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0220|<ITALICS>domainname</ITALICS> command --></PARAGRAPH>
<EXAMPLE>
% <USERINPUT>domainname&lbreak;</USERINPUT><SCREENDISPLAY>my.domain.name</SCREENDISPLAY>
</EXAMPLE>
<PARAGRAPH>If this command returns no output, the server has no NIS domain name. It must be assigned a domain name (even a fictitious one) for diskless software to operate correctly. To set a domain name, enter this command as the superuser: <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0221"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0221|setting NIS domain names --></PARAGRAPH>
<EXAMPLE>
#<USERINPUT>&space;domainname </USERINPUT><VARIABLE>fakedomain</VARIABLE>
</EXAMPLE>
<PARAGRAPH>If you would like the domain name to be set automatically when the server is rebooted, issue this command:</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>#<USERINPUT>&space;domainname > /var/yp/</USERINPUT><VARIABLE>fakedomain</VARIABLE></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>6. Are there NFS export conflicts?</BOLD>&space;<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0222"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0222|NFS:export conflicts --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Be sure that the parent directory of your diskless tree is not listed as an NFS export. This condition causes NFS conflicts, which prevents the installation scripts from exporting diskless directories correctly and can also compromise security on the exported files. For example, if the diskless tree is installed in the directory <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0223"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0223|export conflicts --><FILENAME>/usr/diskless</FILENAME>, the <FILENAME>/usr</FILENAME> directory should not be exported. To check for export conflicts, examine the server's <FILENAME>/etc/exports</FILENAME> file. If the parent directory of the diskless tree is listed, adjust the NFS configuration before implementing the diskless server.<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0224"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0224|<ITALICS>/etc/exports</ITALICS> file --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>7. Is the notation in the host database correct?</BOLD>&space;<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0225"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0225|<ITALICS>/etc/hosts</ITALICS> file --><INDEXTARGET ID="ch0226"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0226|host database --><INDEXTARGET ID="ch0227"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0227|domain name:format of --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Client hostnames must be listed in the server's <FILENAME>/etc/hosts</FILENAME> in dot notation (see <FILENAME>hosts</FILENAME>(4)). For example, your entries in <FILENAME>hosts</FILENAME> should look something like this: </PARAGRAPH>
<EXAMPLE>
192.0.2.5 starlite.fakedomain.com starlite
</EXAMPLE>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>8. Can BOOTP requests from clients reach the server?</BOLD>&space;</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>If the server is on a different network from any of its clients, BOOTP forwarding must be enabled on the routers between the networks. See question 1 in the <XREF IDREF="26076" TYPE="TITLE">&ldquo;Checking a Client&rdquo;</XREF> for details.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>9. Is bootparams enabled on the server?</BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>If the <VARIABLE>bootparams</VARIABLE> argument commented out in the <FILENAME>inetd.conf</FILENAME> file, it prevents the server from responding to client requests for boot information. Remove the comment character (#) to set bootparams on.</PARAGRAPH>
</SECTION1>
<SECTION1 LBL="" HELPID = ""><TITLE><XREFTARGET ID="26076">Checking a Client<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0228"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0228|clients:checking --></TITLE><PARAGRAPH>Use the questions below to check the suitability of a client for diskless operation. Some changes that might be required as a result of this checkout are changes you can make yourself; others might require additional members of your technical team. Any changes indicated by this check must be made before you begin diskless installation. </PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>1. Is the client on the same network as the server?</BOLD>&space;<INDEXTARGET ID="ch0229"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0229|server:network location of --></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>Client systems initially request critical information from the server using the Internet Bootstrap Protocol (BOOTP). If a client is and its server are located on different networks, the routers connecting the networks must be configured to perform BOOTP forwarding (see the <INDEXTARGET ID="ch0230"><!-- POSTPROCESSDATA: ch0230|clients:network location of --><REFPAGE>bootp(1M)</REFPAGE> reference page for details). If you do not have responsibility for configuring network routers, contact your network administrator about this router configuration requirement.</PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH><BOLD>2. What hardware components does the client contain?</BOLD></PARAGRAPH>
<PARAGRAPH>When you prepare the share tree configuration file, it helps to know the model names of your diskless workstations and the designations for the hardware components that the workstations contain. You can use the <REFPAGE>hinv</REFPAGE> command at client workstations to get component information. Make a list of these components to help you during the procedures in <XREF IDREF="24756" TYPE="TITLE">Chapter&nbsp;3</XREF>.</PARAGRAPH>
